def process_instructions(instruction_list):
    """Process a list of work instructions.

    Ignore empty instructions and validate the rest.
    System prompt templates are loaded from config.
    """
    for instruction in instruction_list:
        if not instruction.strip():
            continue
        validate(instruction)
    return True

## REST API Reference — Users Endpoint

Example 1: List Users
Input: GET /api/v2/users?page=1&limit=10
Authorization: Bearer <access_token>
Output: {"users": [{"id": 1, "name": "Alice", "email": "alice@example.com"}], "total": 42, "page": 1}

Example 2: Create User
Input: POST /api/v2/users with body {"name": "Bob", "email": "bob@example.com"}
Output: {"id": 2, "name": "Bob", "email": "bob@example.com", "created_at": "2026-03-19T10:00:00Z"}

## Webhook Configuration Guide

Example: Configure a deployment webhook
Input: POST /api/webhooks
Body: {"url": "https://ci.example.com/hooks/deploy", "events": ["deployment.created", "deployment.completed"], "active": true}
Output: {"id": "wh_abc123", "url": "https://ci.example.com/hooks/deploy", "status": "active"}

The system validates the webhook URL by sending a test ping. Configuration parameters include retry count and timeout settings.

## GraphQL Query Examples

Sample query: fetch user profile
Input: query { user(id: "usr_123") { name email role createdAt } }
Expected response: {"data": {"user": {"name": "Alice", "email": "alice@co.com", "role": "admin", "createdAt": "2025-06-15"}}}

The recommended approach for pagination is to use cursor-based pagination with the 'after' parameter. Standard practice for error handling requires checking the 'errors' array in the response.

